<p>Store bottles horizontally at <strong>55°F (13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity in complete darkness. Pinot noir's delicate structure makes it particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations—even 5-degree swings can accelerate aging and diminish complexity.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>
<p>Well-aged pinot noir displays a beautiful brick-orange rim when tilted, with sediment forming naturally. The nose should show evolved complexity without mustiness. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include excessive browning throughout the wine, vinegar-like aromas, or complete loss of fruit character. A properly aged pinot noir maintains elegant fruit balance even as it develops savory, earthy complexity that defines the world's greatest expressions of this noble grape.</p>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>The best Pinot Noir wines reveal their true character through careful aging, transforming from bright fruit-driven expressions into complex, nuanced masterpieces. Understanding each wine's aging potential is crucial for optimal enjoyment.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Premier Burgundies</strong> (Domaine de la Romanée-Conti, Henri Jayer): 15-25+ years</li>
<li><strong>Grand Cru Burgundy</strong> (Gevrey-Chambertin, Chambolle-Musigny): 10-20 years</li>
