<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Burgundy Pinot Noir and California Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy Pinot Noirs typically showcase higher acidity, earthier mineral notes, and more restrained fruit flavors due to the cooler climate and limestone-rich soils. California Pinot Noirs, particularly from warmer regions like Santa Barbara, tend to be fruit-forward with riper berry flavors and softer tannins. Oregon Pinot Noirs often split the difference, offering Burgundy-like elegance with California's approachable fruit character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because it's typically lighter-bodied with softer tannins than Cabernet Sauvignon or Syrah, making it less overwhelming on the palate. The wine's bright acidity and food-friendly nature make it versatile for pairing, while its complex aromatics help develop your tasting skills. Start with approachable producers like La Crema or Bogle before exploring more complex Burgundies.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I identify a high-quality Pinot Noir without breaking the bank?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for wines from lesser-known regions like Tasmania, Central Otago, or Germany's Baden region, which often offer exceptional quality-to-price ratios. Check for producer consistency—wineries like Cloudline (Oregon) or Mont Rouge (Burgundy) deliver reliable quality under $30. Avoid overly marketed brands and instead seek wines with specific vineyard designations or village appellations, which indicate more careful sourcing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Pinot Noir, and does it matter?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Pinot Noir at 60-65°F (15-18°C), which is slightly cooler than room temperature but warmer than typical refrigerator temperature. This temperature range preserves the wine's delicate aromatics while allowing the fruit flavors to shine without being muted by excessive chill. If your wine is too warm, the alcohol will dominate; too cold, and you'll miss the subtle complexity that makes great Pinot Noir special.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant Pinot Noir, and if so, for how long?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Pinot Noirs don't require decanting due to their naturally lower tannin levels, but young, high-quality bottles can benefit from 30-60 minutes of breathing to open up their aromatics. Older Burgundies (10+ years) should be handled carefully—decant only to separate sediment, not for aeration, as extended air exposure can cause delicate older wines to fade quickly. When in doubt, pour a small taste first to assess whether decanting will help.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying solely based on price—assuming expensive means better quality, or conversely, that cheap wines can't be good. Many wine drinkers also overlook vintage variation in Pinot Noir, which is more sensitive to weather than robust varietals. Additionally, people often buy Pinot Noir from warm climates expecting Burgundy-style elegance, or purchase wines that are too young from producers that require 3-5 years of cellaring to show their best.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">If I love Pinot Noir, what other wines should I try?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Explore Gamay from Beaujolais, which shares Pinot Noir's bright acidity and food-friendliness but with more pronounced fruit character and lower prices. Nebbiolo from Piedmont offers similar elegance and complexity but with more structure, while Sangiovese provides comparable food-pairing versatility. For something closer to home, try Pinot Meunier or lighter-style Grenache, which share Pinot Noir's approachable tannins and aromatic complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age the best Pinot Noirs, and which ones improve with time?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Burgundies from producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti or Louis Jadot can age 15-25 years, developing tertiary aromas of forest floor, leather, and dried roses. Premium California Pinot Noirs from cool-climate producers like Williams Selyem or Kosta Browne typically peak at 8-12 years. Most everyday Pinot Noirs under $30 are best consumed within 3-5 years of vintage, as they're crafted for immediate enjoyment rather than long-term cellaring.</p>
